Denote BC=x.
[asy]
draw((0,0)--(15,0)--(9,10)--cycle);
draw((5,0)--(9,10));
draw(rightanglemark((9,10), (9,0), (15,0)));
label("A", (5,0), S);
label("B", (0,0), W);
label("D", (9,10), N);
label("BC", (7,0), S); label("x", (9,5));
filldraw((15,0)--(15,11)--(9,11)--cycle,mediumgray);
draw((15,1)--(15,0),Arrow);
[/asy]
From right angle $\triangle ABD$ and law of cosine on $\triangle BDC$, \begin{align*} \cos A &= \frac{AB^2+AD^2-BD^2}{2\cdot AB\cdot AD}= \frac{25+AD^2-400}{2\cdot 5\cdot AD}= \frac{AD^2-375}{10\cdot AD},\\  \cos^2 A &= \frac{AB\cdot BD^2+(AD^2-375)^2}{10^2\cdot AD^2}=\frac{25\cdot 400+(AD^2-375)^2}{100\cdot AD^2},\\ \cos A &= \pm \frac{\sqrt{160\cdot AD^4-22500\cdot AD^2+1875^2+1000000}}{100\cdot AD^2}. \end{align*}Since $\cos A$ cannot be negative, \[ 160\cdot AD^4-22500\cdot AD^2+1875^2+1000000=10000\cdot AD^4. \]Simplifying it,  \[ 4\cdot AD^4-22500\cdot AD^2+1875^2+1000000=0. \]Let $AD^2=y$, and throw out the negative real solution,  \[ y\in \left( \frac{5625-\sqrt{625^2-4\cdot 1875^2}}{4},\frac{5625+\sqrt{625^2-4\cdot 1875^2}}{4} \right), \]so \[ \boxed{x >= 8}. \]

</think>Answer $8\ \text{cm}$.</answer>

